		<text id="text01" x="364" y="120" width="380" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">&lt;B&gt;Scenario: &lt;/B&gt;A father plays with his 6-month-old son by making clicking sounds. The father and child enjoy the interchange. However, the son soon becomes overstimulated and looks away. Rather than continue the game, the father has learned that this cue means his child needs a break so he stops the clicking. </content>
		</text>
		<text id="text02" x="357" y="227.6" width="408" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content/>
		</text>
		<text id="text03" x="357" y="241.6" width="398" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content/>
		</text>
		<text id="text04" x="364" y="230" width="382" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">To become attuned with their child, parents need to observe, monitor, and pay attention to the child's environment.</content>
		</text>
		<text id="text05" x="364" y="277" width="381" height="" autosize="H" style="DEFAULT" visible="false" fx="TEXT_SHOW" hidefx="TEXT_HIDE">
			<content translate="true">As parents become acquainted with their child, they become more responsive and able to anticipate their child's needs.</content>
		</text>
	</section>
